  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA255-kiḷavi">iḵtāṟupārttuṟṟatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is what is experienced when seeing the path.</p>
        </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA255">
<l>            kaḻutukāl kiḷara vūrmaṭin taṉṟē</l>
<l>            yurukeḻu marapiṟ kuṟiñci pāṭik</l>
<l>            kaṭiyuṭai viyaṉakark kāṉavar tuñcār</l>
<l>            vayakkaḷiṟu poruta vāḷvari yuḻuvai</l>
<l>            kaṉmukaic cilampiṟ kuḻumu maṉṉō </l>
<l>            meṉṟō ṇekiḻntunām varuntiṉu miṉṟavar</l>
<l>            vārā rāyiṉō naṉṟumaṟ ṟilla</l>
<l>            vuyarvarai yaṭukkat toḷiṟupu miṉṉip</l>
<l>            peyalkāṉ mayaṅkiya poḻutukaḻi pāṉāṭ</l>
<l>            ṭirumaṇi yaravuttērn tuḻala </l>
<l>            vurumuccivan teṟiyu mōṅkuvarai yāṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>While the time of the demons comes up, the village has become inactive.</l>
<l rend="indent2">Singing [their] fearful Kuṟiñci [tune] in the customary way</l>
<l>the forest people(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kāṉavar</term>: here there is reason to consider an emendation to <term xml:lang="ta">kāvalar</term>, as would be much better in tune with topos and context.</note> in [their] protected wide mansion don’t sleep.</l>
<l>Does not<note place="foot">Here the nuance of <term xml:lang="ta">maṉṉō</term> seems to be that of a certain fact which ought to be acknowledged, hence the negative rendering.</note> the bright-striped tiger that has beaten the strong elephant bull</l>
<l rend="indent2">growl on the mountain side in [its] stone cave?</l>
<l rend="indent2">Even though we will suffer, soft shoulders emaciating,</l>
<l>if he does not come today?</l>
<l rend="indent4">[That] would be good indeed</l>
<l rend="indent">– along the high mountain path, where [lightning] flashes brightly</l>
<l rend="indent">on the flank of the high mountain [and] thunder dashes angrily(?),</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that the snake roams about in search of [its] brilliant gem,<note place="foot">The topos of the snake possessing a gem is familiar (cf. KT 239, AN 192, AN 372, PN 294), but here T.V.G. explains that the animal puts this jewel down at night in order to have better light for searching food, and here, since it is notoriously afraid of thunder, its wants to take it back and hide. The sole parallel is to be found in AN 92.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">at midnight, as time passes by, confused by wind [and] raining.</l>
    </lg>
      </div>
